05173nam a22007815i 9780824842376DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20042004hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1029810386  a(OCoLC)1032676845  a(OCoLC)1037980210  a(OCoLC)1041973995  a(OCoLC)1046621198  a(OCoLC)1047011033  a(OCoLC)1049633060  a(OCoLC)1054868915  a97808248423767 a10.1515/97808248423762doi  a(DE-B1597)484291  a(OCoLC)1013948763  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aSOC0020002bisacsh1 aMartinez, D. P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIdentity and Ritual in a Japanese Diving Village :bThe Making and Becoming of Person and Place /cD. P. Martinez. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (264 p.) :billus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1. On the Anthropologist and Her Subject -- tChapter 2. Japan and the Ama -- tChapter 3. Kuzaki: Making Place and Identity -- tChapter 4. Organizing the Village: Dōkyūsei, the Kumi-ai, and the Nifune Festival -- tChapter 5. Keeping the Ie Afloat: Part 1. Diving and Women’s Rituals -- tChapter 6. Keeping the Ie Afloat: Part 2. Fishing, Tourism, and New Year’s Rituals -- tChapter 7. Elders and Ancestors: Making and Becoming -- tChapter 8. Ritual, Gender, and Identity -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThrough her detailed description of a particular place (Kuzaki-cho) at a particular moment in time (the 1980s), D. P. Martinez addresses a variety of issues currently at the fore in the anthropology of Japan: the construction of identity, both for a place and its people; the importance of ritual in a country that describes itself as nonreligious; and the relationship between men and women in a society where gender divisions are still very much in place. Kuzaki is, for the anthropologist, both a microcosm of modernity and an attempt to bring the past into the present. But it must also be understood as a place all of its own. In the 1980s it was one of the few villages where female divers (ama) still collected abalone and other shellfish and where some of its inhabitants continued to make a living as fishermen. Kuzaki was also a kambe, or sacred guild, of Ise Shrine, the most important Shinto shrine in modern Japan—home to Amaterasu, the sun goddess. Kuzaki’s rituals affirmed a national identity in an era when attitudes to modernity and Japaneseness were being challenged by globalization. Martinez enhances her fascinating ethnographic description of a single diving village with a critique of the way in which the anthropology of Japan has developed. The result is a sophisticated investigation by a senior scholar of Japanese studies that, while firmly grounded in empirical data, calls on anthropological theory to construct another means of understanding Japan—both as a society in which the collective is important and as a place where individual ambitions and desires can be expressed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082484237640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824842376423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824842376.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asi